
[1]whet

   WHET, v.t. pret. and pp. whetted or whet. [G.]

   1. To rub for the purpose of sharpening, as an edge tool; to sharpen by
   attrition; as, to whet a sythe or an ax.

   2. To provoke; to excite; to stimulate; as, to whet the appetite.

   3. To provoke; to make angry or acrimonious.

   Since Cassius first did whet me against Cesar, I have not slept.

   To whet on or whet forward, to urge on; to instigate. [Not used nor
   proper.]

                                  WHET, n.

   1. The act of sharpening by friction.

   2. Something that provokes or stimulates the appetite; as sips, drams
   and whets.
